# Shell scripts must check out as LF so Git Bash runs them on Windows. Git's
# autocrlf otherwise checks them out CRLF, and a carriage return breaks bash
# (`set -u\r`, function syntax, here-doc delimiters) - exactly what makes the
# native-Windows local gate fail. POSIX no-op: these files are already LF in git
# and on Linux/macOS checkouts; the attribute only pins the Windows checkout to
# LF as well, so it changes nothing on the POSIX path ubuntu CI exercises.
*.sh text eol=lf
